<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="stakeholder-register">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>pm-traditional</domain>
    <summary>A version-controlled catalog of stakeholders with power, interest, attitude, and engagement strategy — grounded in observable evidence, not assumption.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>stakeholder-management</tag>
      <tag>register</tag>
      <tag>pmi</tag>
      <tag>governance</tag>
      <tag>risk-management</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Stakeholder Register</title>

    <summary>Hidden stakeholders block projects at the worst possible moments. A register built from authoritative directory data (org chart, CRM) rather than the PM's memory surfaces gatekeepers (infosec, procurement, works council) who are systematically missed. Attitude documented with evidence enables targeted engagement; attitude assumed from seniority misleads. The register is the source of truth for all engagement planning and communications.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Hidden stakeholders block projects at the worst possible moments. A register built from authoritative directory data (org chart, CRM) rather than the PM's memory surfaces gatekeepers (infosec, procurement, works council) who are systematically missed. Attitude documented with evidence enables targeted engagement; attitude assumed from seniority misleads. The register is the source of truth for all engagement planning and communications.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any project with more than five stakeholders where "who has authority over what" is not obvious.</item>
        <item>Programs spanning departments, organizations, or jurisdictions.</item>
        <item>Pre-RFP / vendor selection where the buying committee includes hidden influencers.</item>
        <item>Post-merger or post-reorg projects where lines of authority are still being redrawn.</item>
        <item>Compliance-driven projects requiring a documented record of consulted stakeholders.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo founders or one-person projects.</item>
        <item>Single co-located product squads where everyone is in one channel — a MAINTAINERS.md suffices.</item>
        <item>Throwaway internal scripts or hotfixes with no business stakeholder.</item>
        <item>Crisis response with pre-assigned incident command structure.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="register-fields">
      <p>Each entry in the register must carry:</p>
      <list>
        <item>id — unique stable identifier (S-01, S-02, ...); never reuse after deprecation.</item>
        <item>name — full name, validated against an authoritative directory (Entra ID, Workday, CRM); agents must not invent names.</item>
        <item>role — position or function; source from directory, not assumption.</item>
        <item>organization — department or external org.</item>
        <item>category — one of: Sponsor, User, Customer, Team, Regulator, Supplier, Influencer.</item>
        <item>power — H/M/L; documented with source evidence.</item>
        <item>interest — H/M/L.</item>
        <item>impact — H/M/L; how strongly the project affects them.</item>
        <item>attitude — +/0/-/unknown; defaults to "unknown" without behavioral or quoted evidence.</item>
        <item>quadrant — derived from power/interest: Manage Closely / Keep Satisfied / Keep Informed / Monitor.</item>
        <item>cadence — communication frequency; required for all High-power stakeholders.</item>
        <item>owner — PM or team member responsible for this relationship.</item>
        <item>evidence — list of quotes, transcript references, or log entries supporting attitude and power assertions.</item>
        <item>last_engaged — date of most recent substantive interaction.</item>
        <item>hidden_flag — true if discovered via the hidden-stakeholder checklist, not initial analysis.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Store contact information via a secrets manager (e.g., 1Password op:// URL), never inline in the register; registers contain PII and are shared more broadly than contact credentials should be.</statement>
        <rationale>Inline contact data in a shared repo becomes a PII leak vector; referencing by key allows the register to be shared while keeping personal details protected.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="power-interest-grid">
      <p>Plot each stakeholder on the Mendelow 2x2 grid to determine engagement intensity:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Manage Closely (High power, High interest) — actively engage, involve in decisions, weekly contact minimum.</item>
        <item>Keep Satisfied (High power, Low interest) — regular updates with no surprises; engage before decisions that affect them.</item>
        <item>Keep Informed (Low power, High interest) — regular communication, solicit feedback; these are your champions-in-waiting.</item>
        <item>Monitor (Low power, Low interest) — minimal effort; watch for changes in attitude or power.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>For programs with regulatory or political risk, overlay Mitchell-Agle-Wood salience (power × legitimacy × urgency); the 2x2 alone flattens political complexity that drives high-stakes blockers.</statement>
        <rationale>Influence is not the same as seniority; gatekeepers (EAs, infosec PMs, procurement leads) often hold de facto veto power that the 2x2 maps to Low-power because they lack formal title.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="hidden-stakeholder-checklist">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run the hidden-stakeholder checklist at project initiation and at each phase gate; systematic omissions are more common than random ones.</statement>
        <rationale>The same categories are missed on most projects: legal, infosec, procurement, FinOps, accessibility, works council/union, downstream API consumers, regulators. A checklist converts "we forgot" into "we confirmed absent."</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Legal / Compliance — data processing agreements, IP, contracts.</item>
        <item>Information Security — access, encryption, audit trail.</item>
        <item>Procurement / FinOps — vendor contracts, cloud spend approval.</item>
        <item>Accessibility — a11y requirements for regulated or public-facing products.</item>
        <item>Works Council / Union — organizational change requiring co-determination.</item>
        <item>Downstream API / Data Consumers — systems or teams that depend on outputs.</item>
        <item>Regulators / Standards Bodies — external bodies with compliance authority.</item>
        <item>Customer Success / Support — teams absorbing the operational change.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="freshness-and-evidence">
      <rule>
        <statement>Refresh the register at minimum quarterly; monthly during high-volatility periods (post-merger, leadership change, regulator activity); an unrefreshed register is wrong, not just old.</statement>
        <rationale>Stakeholder power and attitude change with organizational events; a stale register leads the PM to engage the wrong people at the wrong intensity, wasting effort and missing real risks.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Every attitude assertion (+/-) must reference at least one behavioral signal (attendance pattern, response time, escalation, direct quote); attitude defaults to "unknown" without evidence.</statement>
        <rationale>Self-reported or assumed attitude is unreliable; observed behavior is more predictive. Requiring evidence also forces the PM to have real conversations rather than guessing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Triangulate attitude from at least two independent signals before updating from "unknown"; a single data point is noise.</statement>
        <rationale>Cross-cultural communication differences, tone misread in email, and politeness norms all produce false signals; corroboration reduces misclassification.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="pii-and-security">
      <rule>
        <statement>Treat the register as confidential: store in a private repo, run a PII scrubber pre-commit to block candid commentary and salary data, encrypt at rest if shared beyond the immediate team.</statement>
        <rationale>Registers contain candid assessments of individuals' attitudes and influence; leaked registers damage relationships and may constitute GDPR Article 9 violations if attitude implies political opinion or health status.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Including candid negative commentary about a stakeholder in a machine-readable field that is passed to third-party LLMs or shared in team channels.</description>
        <reason>Machine-readable candid data is one copy-paste or API call away from the subject; it damages trust, creates legal liability, and inhibits honest assessment in future registers.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-curation">
      <p>The register is one canonical YAML in git: stakeholders/register.yaml. Each entry has id, name, role, organization, category, power, interest, impact, attitude, quadrant, cadence, owner, contact_ref (1Password key), evidence[], last_engaged, hidden_flag. A subagent ingests authoritative directory exports (Entra ID, Workday, Salesforce) plus narrative inputs (kickoff transcript, RFP) and proposes register patches. Two human approvers (PM + sponsor) sign off on attitude/power changes. The register is the source for engagement-plan generation; it does not double as comms plan or RACI.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>The register-curator agent must validate every name against an authoritative directory before proposing an add or update; reject names absent from the source.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs hallucinate plausible names from titles; a register populated with invented people is worse than no register — it creates false confidence in coverage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap agent edit batches at 10 patches per run; require human review on the diff before merge; never allow the agent to deprecate stakeholders autonomously.</statement>
        <rationale>Bulk automated reclassification destroys historical signal and may remove stakeholders who are still active but temporarily quiet; human review preserves context the agent cannot infer.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <note>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent (drives register tasks), custom register-curator-agent (ingests directory + narrative; emits add/update patches with evidence fields), custom directory-loader-agent (pulls org-chart slice into a typed roster for ground truth), custom hidden-stakeholder-agent (runs a checklist and proposes additions), custom attitude-evidence-agent (requires and stores at least one quote / message per assertion), custom salience-scorer-agent (applies Mitchell-Agle-Wood), password-scrubber-agent (runs over the register before commit).</note>
      <note>Best practices: store register in git (YAML), never in a wiki — diffs become history. Require an evidence: field on every attitude or power assertion. Refresh quarterly minimum; monthly during high-volatility periods. Triangulate self-reported attitude with at least one behavioural signal. One canonical register; if Workday or Salesforce holds source data, mirror nightly into the register. Hidden stakeholders review is a recurring task. Contact info via 1Password / secrets manager — reference by op:// key, not inline. Mitchell-Agle-Wood salience overlay for any program with regulator or political risk. Cap register size; if >50 entries, partition by category and operate on slices. Treat the register as confidential — private repo, scrubber pre-commit, encrypted at rest.</note>
    </section>

    <section name="size-and-partitioning">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Maintaining a single register with more than 50-100 entries without partitioning by category or org unit.</description>
        <reason>Registers above 50 entries become unusable for active engagement planning; the PM dilutes attention across too many relationships. Partition by category (Sponsor, Regulator, User, Vendor) and operate on slices.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-gotchas">
      <p>Registers go stale fast; an unrefreshed register is wrong, not just old. Hidden stakeholders (works councils, infosec, procurement, downstream consumers) are systematically missed unless seeded with org-chart context. Registers without behavioural triangulation rely on self-report, which is unreliable for attitude and influence. Influence ≠ seniority; the gatekeepers (EAs, schedulers, infosec PMs) often outrank their nominal role. Power/Interest 2x2 (Mendelow) flattens politics; for high-stakes programs add Mitchell-Agle-Wood salience overlay. LLMs invent plausible names from titles; without grounding in directory data the register is fiction. Confidentiality risk: registers contain PII, candid commentary, salaries, and sometimes regulated PII (GDPR Art. 9 if attitude implies political opinion or health). "Comprehensive" registers (>200 entries) become unusable; engagement focus dilutes. Agents invent people — always ground name validation in an authoritative directory; reject any name absent from source. LLMs default to "supportive" attitude (politeness bias); force a 4-way enum with unknown default and require evidence for +/-. Stakeholder data is regulated PII; never send the register to a third-party LLM without DPA. Bulk reclassification is dangerous; cap agent edits per run and require human review on diff. Stakeholder vs. persona conflation: stakeholder = real named human/role with decision power; persona = synthesized archetype. Separate files. Influence inference from titles alone misses gatekeepers; force the agent to enumerate gatekeepers explicitly. Long-context drift: registers >50 stakeholders blow the prompt; page by category. Cross-cultural miscoding — agents trained on Western norms misread consensus cultures. Add cultural_context system prompt for international initiatives. Sentiment-from-Slack is lossy; never act on a single message. Attribute leakage: do not include candid commentary in machine-readable fields — use a separate notes_private file with stricter ACL. Human-in-the-loop checkpoints (mandatory): adding a stakeholder, attitude change, deprecation, sharing register outside immediate team, salience overlay decisions.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/register-entry.yaml" purpose="YAML template for a single stakeholder entry"/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/register_audit.py" purpose="Audits register completeness and evidence coverage; exits non-zero on issues"/>
    </scripts>

    <commands>
      <command name="python3 scripts/register_audit.py stakeholders/register.yaml">Audit register for completeness and evidence coverage</command>
    </commands>

